        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Upminster | Romford, Essex.</placeName>
                    <date>7 Sept. 1867.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you very much for your suggestion, which I will carry out in the winter.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I find menagerie bones absolutely useless for comparison with those of the same animals of Pleistocene age.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Between wild individuals even of the same recent species there is a large amount of variation, and that variation M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Sanford and myself have used, or rather are using to prove the identity of <hi rend="underline">Felis spelæa</hi> with <hi rend="underline">F. leo</hi>, in the Palæont. Soc.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I am | My dear Sir | Yours truly | W. Boyd Dawkins <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Charles Darwin Esq. F.R.S.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had encouraged Dawkins in his plans to carry out further comparative studies of the dentition of living and extinct representatives within the Rhinocerotidae (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5616A.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. B. Dawkins, 26 August [1867]</ref>). CD may have made a specific suggestion about the work in a reply to the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5618.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. B. Dawkins, 27 August 1867</ref>, although no such letter has been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Dawkins mentioned changes he had observed in the skulls of captive hyenas compared with their wild counterparts in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5618.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter to CD of 27 August 1867</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Dawkins was collaborating with <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6690.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Ayshford Sanford</ref> on a study of British Pleistocene Felidae (Dawkins and Sanford 1866–72). The four-part monograph was published by the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Palaeontographical Society</ref>. The second part of the work, published in 1868, was on <hi rend="italic">Felis spelaea</hi>, the cave lion (now <hi rend="italic">Panthera leo spelaea</hi>). <hi rend="italic">Felis leo</hi> is now <hi rend="italic">Panthera leo.</hi></note>
        </div>        
            
